{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471345","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471345"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:47:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:47:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"295"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"295","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/295"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.03,0,0.73,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"295"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102596"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"295","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/295"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"295"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85070"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"156"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1308"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11402"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31895"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35203"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102596","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102596"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA five-year-old boy is brought into the Emergency Department by his parents with a two-day history of fever, rigors, headache, vomiting, and rash. He has no significant medical history, takes no regular medications and is up to date with all immunisations. On examination, his pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 90/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 25/min, and temperature 38.8\u00b0C. A non-blanching petechial rash is evident over the body, worse in the arms and chest. There is no obvious neurologic deficit. He refuses to open his eyes because it makes his headache worse.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following treatments should be started immediately?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aggressive fluid resuscitation","Oral prednisolone","Midazolam","Intravenous ceftriaxone","Intramuscular benzylpenicillin"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has the clinical features highly suggestive of meningococcal meningitis, with characteristic symptoms and the finding of a non-blanching rash, fever and photophobia. Acute meningococcal disease (caused by the bacterium \u003Cem\u003ENeisseria meningitidis\u003C/em\u003E) is a potentially devastating cause of severe sepsis. The most recognisable presentations of acute meningococcal disease are sepsis with a progressive non-blanching petechial/purpuric rash, and meningitis with or without sepsis and rash. Rarer presentations include septic arthritis, pneumonia, pharyngitis and occult bacteremia. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA third-generation cephalosporin is the drug of choice for the treatment of meningococcal meningitis. Treatment with \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous ceftriaxone\u003C/strong\u003E (or cefotaxime) should be initiated urgently; if access cannot be obtained, the antibiotic should be given \u003Cstrong\u003Eintramuscularly\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIntravenous dexamethasone (not \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E) should be administered prior to or immediately after the first dose of antibiotics, as this can reduce morbidity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnticonvulsants\u003C/strong\u003E (e.g., midazolam) may be given if the child has seizures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluid resuscitation\u003C/strong\u003E must be done cautiously in children due to the risk of cerebral oedema, which is a life-threatening neurological sequelae of acute bacterial meningitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Treatment with a third generation cephalosporin should be started immediately for a case of suspected meningococcal meningitis."],"references":["Rajapaksa S, Starr M. Meningococcal sepsis. Aust Fam Physician.\u00a02010;39:276-8. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2010/may/meningococcal-sepsis","The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. Clinical Practice Guideline on Meningitis and Encephalitis [Internet]. Melbourne (AU): The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital; [cited 2025 May 13]. Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Meningitis_encephalitis/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85070"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"295"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85070","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85070"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-13T09:32:53+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-13T09:33:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"295"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102596"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"positio